dividuals, usually a pair's offspring of the preceding breeding season, may assist the parents in territorial defence and alarm calling, and in the feeding of nestlings and fledglings. Taxonomy Chaetops aurantius was described in 1867 by Edgar Leopold Layard in his book The birds of South Africa. He placed the genus Chaetops in the thrush family. However, DNA studies have shown that the rockjumpers are not closely related to the thrushes – they are possibly basal passerida, and appear to be related to the rail-babbler and the rockfowl. Some authorities (notably Dickinson and Christidis) treat the two rockjumpers as a single species, Chaetops frenatus, with two subspecies. Gallery References External links Media related to Chaetops aurantius at Wikimedia Commons Data related to Chaetops aurantius at Wikispecies Drakensberg/Orangebreasted Rockjumper - Species text in The Atlas of Southern African Birds.", "shortSummary": "The Drakensberg rockjumper or orange-breasted rockjumper (Chaetops aurantius) is a medium-sized insectivorous passerine bird endemic to the…", "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Drakensberg_rockjumper_2012_11_11_2064_crop.jpg/960px-Drakensberg_rockjumper_2012_11_11_2064_crop.jpg", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-chaetops", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-chaetops-aurantius", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genus": "taxonomy-genus-chaetops", "species": "taxonomy-species-chaetops-aurantius"}, "expandable": true, "x": -253.95, "y": 550.95, "z": -23.13}, {"id": "taxonomy-genus-chaetops", "name": "Chaetops", "latinName": "Chaetops", "type": "taxonomy", "taxonomyLevel": "genus", "summary": "Chaetops（Chaetops）是图谱中的分类级分类节点，当前关联2种鸟类，如Cape rockjumper、Drakensberg rockjumper。", "expandable": true, "memberCount": 2, "x": 458.3